</li></ul></div>
<p></p><div class="folderlabel" onclick="togglefolder('folder12');">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Western Animation&nbsp;</div><div id="folder12" class="folder" isfolder="true" style="display:block;">
<ul><li> <em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/WesternAnimation/SupermanTheAnimatedSeries" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/WesternAnimation/SupermanTheAnimatedSeries">Superman: The Animated Series</a></em> has <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/ComicBook/LexLuthor" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/ComicBook/LexLuthor">Lex Luthor</a>'s bodyguard, Mercy Graves, who wears a chauffeur uniform with very tight pants. Mercy returned as Lex's bodyguard in <em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/WesternAnimation/TheBatman" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/WesternAnimation/TheBatman">The Batman</a></em> and <em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/WesternAnimation/YoungJustice" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/WesternAnimation/YoungJustice">Young Justice</a></em>.
</li><li> <em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/WesternAnimation/BatmanTheAnimatedSeries" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/WesternAnimation/BatmanTheAnimatedSeries">Batman: The Animated Series</a></em> examples:
<ul><li> Mr. Freeze of all people employed <a class="urllink" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5M7ueGZypYE">a goon squad of women wearing<img src="https://static.tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pub/external_link.gif" height="12" width="12" style="border:none;"></a> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ExposedToTheElements" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ExposedToTheElements">impossibly short leg-baring parka-type outfits</a>. One would hope they're actually wearing warm and comfy flesh-colored tights.
</li><li> The Penguin had henchwomen Jay, Lark and Raven.
</li><li> Calendar Girl had the gender-flipped version; bodyguards who looked like Chippendales Dancers.
</li></ul></li><li> In the <em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/WesternAnimation/BatmanTheBraveAndTheBold" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/WesternAnimation/BatmanTheBraveAndTheBold">Batman: The Brave and the Bold</a></em> episode "The Mask of Matches Malone!", Batman poses as mobster Matches Malone and has Black Canary, Huntress and Catwoman pose as his bodyguards. After being conked on the head <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/AmnesiacLiar" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/AmnesiacLiar">and believing himself to be a true mobster</a>, Malone is shown with several other henchwomen/bodyguards.
<ul><li> Another episode has Lashina and Stompa, Mongal's female enforcers. (In the comics, Lashina and Stompa are the names of two of Darkseid's Female Furies.)
</li></ul></li><li> <em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/WesternAnimation/TheBatman" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/WesternAnimation/TheBatman">The Batman</a></em> had the Kabuki Twins, the Penguin's two female bodyguards. The above-mentioned Mercy Graves also appeared as Luthor's bodyguard in a later episode. The final season also introduced attractive female sidekicks for Mirror Master and Firefly, despite both villains generally working alone in the comics.
</li><li> Spoiler alert: In <em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/WesternAnimation/LoveDeathAndRobots" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/WesternAnimation/LoveDeathAndRobots">Love, Death &amp; Robots</a></em> episode <span class="spoiler" title="you can set spoilers visible by default on your profile">1, the gangster's eye candy is revealed to be a bodyguard and minion</span> and that's not <span class="spoiler" title="you can set spoilers visible by default on your profile">even the <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TwistEnding" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TwistEnding">Twist Ending</a>.</span>
</li></ul></div>
<p></p><div class="folderlabel" onclick="togglefolder('folder13');">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Real Life&nbsp;</div><div id="folder13" class="folder" isfolder="true" style="display:block;">
<ul><li> <a class="urllink" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chandragupta_Maurya">Chandragupta Maurya<img src="https://static.tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pub/external_link.gif" height="12" width="12" style="border:none;"></a>, the founder of the Maurya Empire in ancient India (322 - 185 BCE) and thus making this trope <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/OlderThanFeudalism" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/OlderThanFeudalism">Older Than Feudalism</a>, had an army of more than 500 highly-trained bodyguards of Greek and Indian warrior women because he considered them less likely to participate on a coup conspiracy (and considering that he lived to renounce his kingdom and sit his son Bindusara on the throne in 297 BCE, he may have had a point there). This custom was also used by other Indian rulers according to chronicler Strabo.
</li><li> <a class="urllink" href="https://static.tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pub/images/Green_Nuns.jpg">The 40-woman 'Green Nuns'<img src="https://static.tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pub/external_link.gif" height="12" width="12" style="border:none;"></a><small>&loz;</small> of the deceased Libyan dictator <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/UsefulNotes/MuammarGaddafi" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/UsefulNotes/MuammarGaddafi">Muammar al-Gaddafi</a> (<a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/SpellMyNameWithAnS" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/SpellMyNameWithAnS">may his spellings be many</a>). Muammar claimed that the "Green Nuns" were formed to get the Libyan people to warm up to the idea of women in the armed forces. How much of that you believe is up to you...
<ul><li> Turns out that they were less bodyguards and more a private harem mainly full of women who weren't there of their own free will - which might explain how none of them stayed around to protect him, once things went south.
</li></ul></li><li> The non-fiction book <em>Gomorrah</em> mentioned that female Camorra gang bosses use female bodyguards. They often dress in yellow jumpsuits in homage to Uma Thurman's outfit in <em><a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/KillBill" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/KillBill">Kill Bill</a></em>.
</li><li> The <a class="urllink" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dahomey_Amazons">Dahomey Amazons<img src="https://static.tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pub/external_link.gif" height="12" width="12" style="border:none;"></a> of Benin, who went from royal harem to <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/PraetorianGuard" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/PraetorianGuard">Praetorian Guard</a> before being expanded into an all-out <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/AmazonBrigade" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/AmazonBrigade">Amazon Brigade</a>.
</li><li> <a class="urllink" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Madame_Nhu">Madame Nhu<img src="https://static.tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pub/external_link.gif" height="12" width="12" style="border:none;"></a>, the first lady of South Vietnam from 1955 to 1963 who infamously referred to the self-immolation of a Buddhist monk in protest of her brother-in-law's policies as a "Buddhist barbecue" and was herself referred to by some as "the <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/DragonLady" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/DragonLady">Dragon Lady</a>," had a team of all female bodyguards.
</li><li> Chinese businesswomen are <a class="urllink" href="http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-15688685">starting to seek out young female bodyguards<img src="https://static.tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pub/external_link.gif" height="12" width="12" style="border:none;"></a> who are less conspicuous than their burly male counterparts. <a class="urllink" href="http://www.chinawhisper.com/pictures-pretty-china-female-bodyguards-under-hard-training">They are still subjected to the same intense training.<img src="https://static.tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pub/external_link.gif" height="12" width="12" style="border:none;"></a>
<ul><li> More common than most people think. When an important person is accompanied by big men in suits and what appears to be a secretary, she's often one of the bodyguards as well.
</li><li> usually done so potential threats to the VIP are distracted by the larger intimidating male bodyguards, who often is the partner of the female bodyguard in question. To quote one male member of a Bodyguard duo like this: "I can toss two or three guys around, easy, but her? she could disassemble people before they even knew what was happening."
</li><li> Exemplified in <a class="urllink" href="https://notalwaysright.com/secure-in-her-ability/59399/">this<img src="https://static.tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pub/external_link.gif" height="12" width="12" style="border:none;"></a> <a class="twikilink" href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Website/NotAlwaysWorking" title="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Website/NotAlwaysWorking">Not Always Working</a> story.
</li></ul><div class="indent"><strong>Instructor:</strong> (...) Celebrities hire guys like you to stand in front of them and look scary; millionaire businessmen hire people like her if they want real security.
</div></li><li> <a class="urllink" href="http://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-39283407">Edemm<img src="https://static.tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pub/external_link.gif" height="12" width="12" style="border:none;"></a> is a Spanish organization of female bodyguards meant to protect women from abusive partners.
</li></ul></div>
<hr>
</div>
